    imageAlt: "Person thinking with abstract light patterns",
    author: "Dr. Sarah Jenkins",
    authorRole: "Research Psychologist",
    sections: [
      { type: "p", content: "Few debates in applied psychology generate more heat than the question of IQ versus emotional intelligence (EQ). Corporate training programs have invested billions in EQ development, business bestsellers declare emotional intelligence 'more important than IQ,' and hiring managers increasingly screen candidates on empathy and self-awareness. Meanwhile, decades of rigorous psychometric research continue to show that general cognitive ability (g) is the single most powerful predictor of academic and occupational success. So who is right?" },
      { type: "h2", content: "Defining the Two Constructs" },
      { type: "p", content: "IQ measures cognitive ability — the capacity for abstract reasoning, working memory, processing speed, and pattern recognition. Emotional intelligence, as originally defined by Peter Salovey and John Mayer in 1990, refers to the ability to perceive emotions accurately, use emotions to facilitate thought, understand emotional meanings, and regulate emotions in oneself and others. This ability-based model of EQ is distinct from the popular 'mixed models' (like Daniel Goleman's) that bundle personality traits, social skills, and motivational tendencies into the EQ label." },
      { type: "p", content: "The ability-based model of EQ can be measured reliably and shows modest but genuine correlations with both IQ (around r = 0.30) and personality traits like agreeableness and openness. It is a real construct with genuine predictive validity. The mixed-model EQ inventories, however, are largely personality measures rebranded — their incremental predictive validity above standard personality scales is often negligible." },
      { type: "h2", content: "What the Research Actually Shows" },
      { type: "p", content: "Across hundreds of studies and meta-analyses, general cognitive ability (g / IQ) consistently predicts job performance across all occupational categories — with population-weighted validity coefficients of approximately r = 0.50 to 0.55 for complex jobs. No other measured psychological variable comes close to this predictive power for complex jobs. For military performance, academic achievement, and earnings, the correlation with IQ is similarly robust and replicates across cultures and decades." },
      { type: "p", content: "Ability-based EQ shows incremental validity above cognitive ability and personality for specific outcomes — notably leader emergence, quality of social relationships, negotiation effectiveness, and performance in roles requiring sustained interpersonal collaboration. A 2004 meta-analysis by O'Boyle et al. found that EQ predicted job performance above and beyond both personality and IQ, particularly in jobs with high emotional labor demands such as teaching, nursing, social work, and sales." },
      { type: "blockquote", content: "\"The question isn't IQ versus EQ — it's understanding when each matters and how they interact.\" — John Mayer, co-originator of the EQ construct" },
      { type: "h2", content: "Domain Specificity: Where Each Shines" },
      { type: "p", content: "A more nuanced picture emerges when we look at specific life domains rather than treating 'success' as monolithic. For academic achievement across all subjects, IQ is the dominant predictor — EQ adds relatively little above cognitive ability and conscientiousness. For leadership effectiveness, the picture is more balanced: high-IQ leaders outperform on complex strategic tasks, while higher-EQ leaders build stronger teams and navigate organizational politics more effectively. The most successful executives tend to be above average on both." },
      { type: "p", content: "For romantic relationship quality, EQ appears to matter considerably more than IQ. Partners who can accurately perceive and respond to each other's emotional states, manage their own emotional reactions during conflict, and express empathy effectively show higher relationship satisfaction and stability — outcomes that are only weakly predicted by IQ." },
      { type: "h2", content: "The Real Question: Can You Change Either?" },
      { type: "p", content: "Here is where the debate becomes practically relevant. Core cognitive ability (fluid intelligence and g) is substantially heritable and relatively stable in adulthood. While environmental factors matter — particularly in early childhood — there is no reliably effective intervention that significantly raises adult IQ. Emotional intelligence, by contrast, shows much greater malleability. Longitudinal studies of EQ development show steady increases with age, mentorship, deliberate practice of social skills, and structured feedback. Corporate EQ training programs show modest but real effects when well-designed." },
      { type: "p", content: "The practical implication: if you want to maximize life success, leverage your cognitive strengths for career domain selection, and invest in emotional and social skills for relationship quality, leadership effectiveness, and career advancement. IQ determines your 'floor' for complex cognitive tasks; EQ influences how effectively you collaborate, lead, and adapt. Both matter — but in different domains, at different life stages, and in ways that complement rather than compete with each other." },
    ]
